Agaricaceae Agaricus sp. Chocolate-Brown / Purple-Brown Brown 1 Chocolate-Brown 2 Ground 3 Ground | Various. Roadsides, Grass, Meadows, Woodland... etc. Free 4 Free / Barely Attached | Remote from stem. Pink when young. Dark brown and free or almost free at maturity. Close / Crowded Saprobic Medium 5 Yes 6 Fibrous 7 Fibrous / Scaly / None | Glabrous or with flattened fibers, not brightly Colored. Fleshy Hollow 8 Hollow / None | n/a Medium / Large | Veil: Yes | Flesh thick, white. Usually white / gray / brown. Flesh, cap margin, base of stipe can often bruise yellow / red. Agrocybe are smaller and don't always have a partial veil. Chemical Reactions: KOH- negative or yellow-orange Agaricus bitorquis, Agaricus arvensis, Agaricus campestris, Agaricus nanaugustus, Agaricus xanthodermus Contains many species. Some are easy, some are extremely difficult.

Margin with gray-brown ring fragments None 8 Bulbous Base / None | Pink under gray-brown powder, with basal bulb from mycelium binding substrate Small | Veil: Yes / No | Flesh thin, white turning red Can seem similar to Agaricus due to pink free gills, but Agaricus are bigger. Spore Color and powdery cap suface sets Melanophyllum apart. If spores are white and: attached gills, Cystoderma, if free, Lepiota. NaN Melanophyllum haematospermum Only species for this genus in North East is M. haematospermum

Saprobic probably Small 5 No 6 Depressed 7 Depressed / Striate / None | Blocky or squarish at first, then convex with possible sunken center, striate. Tacky when fresh but soon dry. Bald. Orange with a whitish margin when young, soon yellowish orange overall with a darker orange center None 8 None | Dry, bald, Colored like cap. Basal mycelium white. Small | Veil: No | Minutely fibrillose throughout Lots of look alikes. Deeply deccurent gills will separate from most marasmiois and mycenoid contenders. Growing in moss will separate from Xeromphalina kauffmanii and Xeromphalina campanella, which grow in dense clusters on hardwood. Usually a bit larger: Cantharellus minor and Hygrocybe cantharellus NaN Rickenella fibula Only species of its genus, but difficult due to many small and simliar mushrooms.

Tricholomataceae Catathelasma sp. White Pale 1 White 2 Ground 3 Ground | Under conifers, alone or scattered. Decurrent 4 Decurrent / Bluntly Attached | Whitish Mycorrhizal Large 5 Yes 6 Fibrous 7 Fibrous / None | Whitish cap that develops grayish fibrils and spots. Volva 8 Volva / Rooting / None | Often swollen in the middle, somewhat rooting. Large | Veil: Yes | Tough. Ring prominant and double. Odor and taste are mild or slightly unpleasant. Not mealy. Flesh is white and hard. Tricholoma caligatum group do not have decurrent gills, no double ring, and are sometimes under hardwoods. Tricholoma murrillianum group are similar, but whiter and have a spicy odor. NaN Catathelasma ventricosum The only species found in the North East is C. ventricosum
